      "content": "The critics of substantive due process are often seen as trying to maintain the status quo and prevent the expansion of civil rights. They argue that the Constitution should be interpreted strictly, focusing on procedural due process to ensure fair treatment under the law. However, this perspective can be viewed as a way to limit the government's ability to protect individual rights and liberties. By emphasizing procedural due process, they may inadvertently hinder progress in advancing civil rights and personal freedoms. It's important to recognize that substantive due process serves as a necessary counterbalance to government power, ensuring that our fundamental rights are not just protected by fair procedures, but also by the very essence of our constitutional values.",
